Name: John Doe
Age: 48
Gender: Male
Occupation: IT Professional
Ethnicity: African American
Past Medical History: Hypertension, Obesity, and Sleep Apnea

Presentation of Case:
John Doe is a 48-year-old African American IT professional who presented to the emergency department with a fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He reported feeling fatigued and experiencing body aches for the past three days. He has a history of hypertension, obesity, and sleep apnea, but he does not smoke or use any recreational drugs. He was not vaccinated against COVID-19. Upon arrival, John's oxygen saturation was 88% on room air, and his vital signs were stable. The chest x-ray showed bilateral interstitial infiltrates consistent with COVID-19. He was admitted to the hospital and started on supplemental oxygen and Remdesivir. His condition gradually improved over the next few days, and he was discharged after seven days of hospitalization. John was advised to follow up with his primary care physician and get vaccinated against COVID-19.

Name: John Smith
Age: 58
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Caucasian
Past Medical History: Hypertension, type 2 diabetes

Presentation of Case:

John Smith, a 58-year-old Caucasian male, presented to the emergency department with a cough, shortness of breath, and fever for the past 3 days. He reported that he had been feeling fatigued and had lost his sense of taste and smell. John works as a construction worker and had no recent travel history. He was diagnosed with hypertension and type 2 diabetes 5 years ago and has been taking medication for it.

On examination, John's vital signs were stable, but he had bilateral crackles on lung auscultation, and his oxygen saturation was 90% on room air. A COVID-19 test was performed, which came back positive. John was admitted to the hospital and started on oxygen therapy and antiviral medication. His condition improved over the next few days, and he was discharged from the hospital after a week.

Name: John Smith 
Age: 45 
Gender: Male 
Occupation: Office Manager 
Ethnicity: Caucasian 
Past Medical History: Hypertension, Obesity 

Presentation of Case:

John Smith, a 45-year-old male office manager, presented to the emergency department with complaints of fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He reported that his symptoms began 5 days ago and have been progressively worsening. He denied any recent travel or exposure to individuals with COVID-19, but reported attending a large gathering at a local restaurant the week before. 

Upon examination, John was found to have a fever of 101.5°F, tachycardia, and tachypnea. His oxygen saturation was 89% on room air and improved to 93% on 4L of nasal cannula oxygen. A chest X-ray showed bilateral infiltrates consistent with COVID-19 pneumonia. 

John was admitted to the hospital and started on supplemental oxygen, intravenous fluids, and remdesivir. He remained hospitalized for 10 days and was eventually discharged with instructions to self-quarantine for an additional 14 days.

Name: John Doe
Age: 45
Gender: Male
Occupation: Construction worker
Ethnicity: Hispanic
Past Medical History: Hypertension, obesity

Presentation of Case:
John Doe presents to the emergency department with a two-day history of fever, cough, and shortness of breath. He reports feeling fatigued and has lost his appetite. His wife also tested positive for COVID-19 two weeks ago. He has a history of hypertension and obesity but is otherwise healthy. On examination, his temperature is 101°F, and his oxygen saturation is 92% on room air. Lung auscultation reveals bilateral crackles. A chest X-ray shows bilateral infiltrates. A COVID-19 test is performed, which comes back positive. He is admitted to the hospital and started on oxygen therapy and antiviral medication.
